{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-874955c652a84d89", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tMADB: A Large-Scale Music Aesthetics Dataset with\n2\tProfessional and Multi-Dimensional Annotations\n3\tSirui Zhang1,2 , Tianle Wang1,2 , Xinyi Tong1,2 , Peiyang Yu1,2 , Jishang Chen1,2 ,\n4\tLiangke Zhao1,2 , Haoxin Zhang1,2 , Duo Xu2,3,∗ , Xin Jin2,4,∗ , Feng Yu1,∗ , Songchun Zhu2,5,∗\n5\t1\n6\t\n7\tCentral Conservatory of Music, China\n8\tBeijing Institute for General Artificial Intelligence\n9\t3\n10\tTianjin Conservatory of Music\n11\t4\n12\tBeijing Electronic Science and Technology Institute\n13\t5\n14\tPeking University\n15\t∗\n16\tCorresponding authors\n17\t\n18\tarXiv:2607.06929v1 [cs.SD] 8 Jul 2026\n19\t\n20\t2\n21\t\n22\tAbstract\n23\tMusic aesthetic assessment is a challenging yet underexplored problem, requiring\n24\tmodels to capture fine-grained, multi-dimensional human perceptual judgments.\n25\tProgress in this area has been limited by the lack of large-scale datasets with\n26\tstructured aesthetic annotations.\n27\tWe introduce MADB, a large-scale dataset and benchmark comprising 9,999 tracks\n28\tannotated by 30 trained annotators. Each track is rated by around 10 annotators\n29\tacross 10 perceptual dimensions and one overall score, with additional textual\n30\tcomments for multimodal analysis.\n31\tWe establish a unified evaluation framework over multiple pretrained models.\n32\tResults reveal substantial gaps between model predictions and human judgments,\n33\texposing key limitations of current approaches.\n34\tMADB provides a new benchmark for human-aligned music understanding. Project\n35\tpage: https://github.com/knownree/madb\n36\t\n37\tFigure 1: Annotation examples\n38\t\n39\tPreprint.\n40\t\n41\t\f1\n42\t\n43\tIntroduction\n44\t\n45\tThe rapid development of generative music models Agostinelli et al. [2023], Lei et al. [2025], Yuan\n46\tet al. [2025] has led to a surge in AI-generated music, creating an urgent need for automatic evaluation\n47\taligned with human aesthetic preferences. The rapid expansion of AI-generated music not only\n48\tcreates diverse application scenarios for automatic aesthetic evaluation, but also elevates it to a\n49\tcritical component in modern music generation pipelines, with applications in content filtering,\n50\trecommendation, and reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF).\n51\tDespite these advances, current models often fail to produce music that aligns with human expectations, exhibiting issues such as structural incoherence and limited expressiveness Agostinelli et al.\n52\t[2023], Copet et al. [2024]. This gap highlights the need for reliable aesthetic evaluation models that\n53\tcan accurately reflect human perception.\n54\tMusic aesthetic assessment is inherently challenging. It is subjective and exhibits substantial interindividual variability, while also requiring the modeling of relatively stable and generalizable criteria\n55\tgrounded in domain knowledge. Moreover, aesthetic evaluation in music relies heavily on expertise:\n56\ttrained musicians can provide fine-grained and technically grounded assessments, explaining not\n57\tonly whether a piece is preferred but also why it is perceived as aesthetically effective or flawed. This\n58\tdual requirement of subjectivity and expertise makes large-scale, high-quality annotation particularly\n59\tchallenging.\n60\tHowever, existing datasets for music aesthetic evaluation remain limited in scale, number of annotators, and coverage of perceptual dimensions, and often rely on single-score annotations without\n61\tricher supervision such as multi-dimensional ratings or textual feedback.\n62\tTo address these challenges, we make the following contributions:\n63\tA multidimensional music aesthetic annotation framework. We define an evaluation framework\n64\twith one overall score and 10 fine-grained perceptual dimensions, supported by annotation guidelines\n65\tto ensure consistency.\n66\tA large-scale music aesthetics dataset and benchmark. We construct MADB, a dataset of 9999\n67\ttracks annotated by trained annotators, each rated by 9–11 annotators across all dimensions, with\n68\tadditional textual comments.\n69\tA unified benchmark for music aesthetic assessment. We evaluate multiple pretrained models,\n70\tincluding CLAP-based approaches, under a unified framework. Results show that current models\n71\tcapture only partial aesthetic information, revealing the difficulty of the task and the need for improved\n72\trepresentations.\n73\t\n74\t2\n75\t\n76\tRelated Work\n77\t\n78\t2.1\n79\t\n80\tMusic Aesthetic Evaluation and Datasets\n81\t\n82\tEarly studies on music aesthetics in the MIR community mainly focused on perceptual modeling\n83\twith handcrafted musical features. For instance, Marias et al. adopted musical tension dynamics as a\n84\tsurrogate indicator of aesthetic quality. Subsequent work by Xin Jin et al. Jin et al. [2024a, 2023]\n85\tfurther combined traditional feature engineering with neural networks to regress aesthetic scores\n86\tfrom hand-designed acoustic features. Nevertheless, these methods are constrained by conventional\n87\tMIR paradigms and exhibit limited representation capacity compared to modern Transformer-based\n88\tmodels.\n89\tIn contrast, aesthetic evaluation in image and video domains has achieved remarkable progress via\n90\tTransformer architectures trained on large-scale expert-annotated corpora. Xin Jin’s team has built\n91\tcomprehensive aesthetic models for visual content Jin et al. [2024b], Qiao et al. [2025], Jiang et al.\n92\t[2026] and constructed large-scale datasets annotated by professionals from art and film institutions,\n93\tenabling the learning of high-level aesthetic representations.\n94\tIn the music domain, several benchmark datasets have been proposed, such as MusicEval Liu\n95\tet al. [2025] and SongEval Yao et al. [2025], which provide basic benchmarks for music aesthetic\n96\tevaluation. However, these datasets suffer from limited data scale, insufficient annotator participation,\n97\tand incomplete coverage of perceptual dimensions. Most existing datasets only provide single-value\n98\t2\n99\t\n100\t\faesthetic ratings and lack rich supervisory signals such as multi-dimensional perceptual scoring and\n101\ttextual subjective feedback, making them inadequate for capturing the complexity of human music\n102\taesthetics.\n103\t2.2\n104\t\n105\tMusic Representation Learning\n106\t\n107\tSelf-supervised learning has substantially advanced music representation learning in recent years\n108\tvan den Oord et al. [2019], Baevski et al. [2020]. Pre-trained models including MuQ Zhu et al. [2025]\n109\tand MERT Li et al. [2024] learn universal audio representations from large-scale music corpora\n110\tand yield promising transfer performance across downstream MIR tasks. Moreover, models such as\n111\tPANNs Kong et al. [2020] and HTSAT Chen et al. [2022] have also been widely adopted. These pretrained models can effectively capture diverse acoustic and musical characteristics, including timbre,\n112\trhythm, and structural patterns, which are inherently correlated with human aesthetic perception.\n113\tHowever, they are not explicitly optimized for perceptual or aesthetic modeling, nor do they incorporate structured aesthetic dimensions and subjective human evaluation signals. It remains an open\n114\tproblem to what extent general-purpose music representations can align with fine-grained human\n115\taesthetic judgments.\n116\t2.3\n117\t\n118\tMusic-Text Cross-Modal Learning\n119\t\n120\tMultimodal research has made considerable progress in aligning music and textual representations.\n121\tCLAP Wu et al. [2024] learns unified audio-text embeddings via contrastive learning. As a foundational framework, CLIP Radford et al. [2021] also verifies the efficacy of large-scale cross-modal\n122\talignment across perceptual domains. Extended frameworks such as CLAMP3 Wu et al. [2025]\n123\tfurther integrate structured textual attributes to enhance fine-grained cross-modal alignment.\n124\tMusic-text multimodal models offer strong capability to associate audio content with semantic and\n125\tcontextual descriptions. Most existing methods primarily concentrate on coarse-grained attributes\n126\tsuch as music genre and general mood. By contrast, rich textual subjective feedback, which is rarely\n127\texploited in current literature, holds great potential for modeling fine-grained perceptual and aesthetic\n128\ttraits, highlighting a promising direction for injecting human-centered perceptual knowledge into\n129\tmusic understanding systems.\n130\t\n131\t3\n132\t\n133\tMADB Dataset and Benchmark\n134\t\n135\t3.1\n136\t\n137\tAesthetic Annotation Framework\n138\t\n139\tTo model the multi-dimensional nature of music perception, we design a structured annotation\n140\tframework consisting of 10 perceptual dimensions and one overall score. These dimensions capture\n141\tcomplementary aspects of musical experience, including melody, arrangement, rhythm, structure,\n142\tperformance, and production-related attributes.\n143\tNot all dimensions are applicable to every track. For non-applicable cases (e.g., singing-related\n144\tattributes for instrumental music), annotators assign a score of 0. These entries are retained as\n145\tnon-applicable labels and excluded from downstream model optimization.\n146\tThe 10 dimensions cover key aspects of music production, including melody perception and emotion,\n147\trhythm and structure, arrangement quality and expressiveness, performance-related attributes such\n148\tas emotion and technical skill, and post-production effects. These dimensions jointly reflect both\n149\tlow-level acoustic qualities and high-level perceptual judgments.\n150\tThe dimensions are organized to align with the major stages of the music production pipeline,\n151\tincluding composition, arrangement, performance, and post-production. This formulation provides a\n152\tstructured decomposition of music aesthetics and enables systematic analysis of different perceptual\n153\tfactors.\n154\tIn addition to fine-grained annotations, we collect an overall aesthetic score representing the annotator’s holistic judgment. This score is not defined as a fixed aggregation of individual dimensions, but\n155\tinstead reflects a higher-level perceptual integration process.\n156\t3\n157\t\n158\t\fTable 1: Music Aesthetic Dimensions\n159\tInterpretation\n160\tMelodic perception refers to the pleasantness and structural\n161\tcoherence of a melody, including the naturalness of pitch\n162\tprogression and overall continuity.\n163\tMelodic emotion measures the intensity and expressiveness of\n164\temotional content conveyed by the melody, including clarity and\n165\temotional impact.\n166\trhythm\n167\tRhythmic perception refers to the appropriateness and clarity of\n168\tperception\n169\trhythmic patterns, as well as their alignment with emotional\n170\tprogression.\n171\tstructure\n172\tStructural perception refers to the clarity, diversity, and novelty of\n173\tperception\n174\tmusical structure, as well as the contrast and organization between\n175\tsections.\n176\tArrangement arrangement Arrangement perception refers to the appropriateness and\n177\tStage\n178\tperception\n179\tcoherence of arrangement and instrumentation, including timbre\n180\tselection, accompaniment, harmonic design, and overall sonic\n181\tbalance.\n182\tarrangement Arrangement emotion measures how well instrumentation and\n183\temotion\n184\tarrangement support emotional expression, including the\n185\talignment of timbre, orchestration, and atmosphere with the\n186\tintended affect.\n187\tperformance Performance and singing emotion measures the clarity, intensity,\n188\tPerformance\n189\tand singing and emotional impact conveyed through instrumental performance\n190\tStage\n191\temotion\n192\tor singing.\n193\tenunciation Articulation and singing technique refers to lyrical clarity, vocal\n194\tand singing timbre, voice control, and the appropriateness and quality of\n195\tskill\n196\tsinging techniques.\n197\tperformance Instrumental technique refers to the timbral quality and technical\n198\tskill\n199\texecution in instrumental performance, including techniques such\n200\tas vibrato and tonguing.\n201\tPostsound\n202\tAudio effects perception refers to the appropriateness of effects\n203\tproduction\n204\teffect\n205\tand mixing, including effects usage, track balance, and overall\n206\tStage\n207\tperception\n208\tclarity and coherence of the sound.\n209\tFinal\n210\toverall\n211\tThe overall score represents a holistic evaluation of the music’s\n212\tproduction\n213\tscore\n214\taesthetic quality, reflecting the integrated perception of multiple\n215\tattributes and the overall listening experience.\n216\tType\n217\t\n218\tAttribute\n219\tmelody\n220\tComposition perception\n221\tStage\n222\tmelody\n223\temotion\n224\t\n225\t3.2\n226\t\n227\tSemantic Annotations\n228\t\n229\tIn addition to numerical ratings, MADB includes semantic annotations to enrich the representation of\n230\tmusic aesthetics. Specifically, each track is associated with short textual comments and tag-based\n231\tlabels.\n232\tAnnotators are required to provide brief textual comments(around 50 words) describing their aesthetic\n233\timpressions of the music. These comments serve as complementary explanations for the numerical\n234\tscores and provide insight into the reasoning process behind human aesthetic judgments. The\n235\tcomments were originally written in Chinese and subsequently translated into English using Qwen2.5Instruct. Comments those less than 10 words will be ignored.\n236\tWe further define two tag-based annotation dimensions: genre and emotion. Each track is assigned\n237\tup to two genre labels and up to two emotion labels from 10 genre labels and 6 emotion labels. These\n238\ttags provide high-level semantic context and facilitate future research on multi-modal learning and\n239\tcross-modal alignment. The complete list of tags is provided in the Appendix.\n240\tThe combination of numerical ratings, textual comments, and semantic tags enables MADB to\n241\tsupport both perceptual modeling and multi-modal aesthetic analysis.\n242\t4\n243\t\n244\t\f3.3\n245\t\n246\tData Sources\n247\t\n248\tThe MADB dataset is constructed from four complementary sources to ensure diversity in musical\n249\tstyle, production quality, and generation paradigm.\n250\tThe first subset consists of 2,799 manually collected tracks curated from online platforms. This\n251\tsubset includes both professionally produced music (e.g., canonical works such as famous classical\n252\tmusics) and widely consumed popular content (e.g., short-video platform music), as well as tracks\n253\twith varying production quality such as royalty-free or publicly available music. This design aims to\n254\tcapture a broad spectrum of real-world listening scenarios.\n255\tThe second and third subsets consist of AI-generated music. Specifically, 1,000 tracks are generated\n256\tby the Suno system, including a subset conditioned on existing song lyrics, and 1,800 tracks are\n257\tgenerated by the Levo system. These samples introduce diverse generative styles and enable the\n258\tevaluation of aesthetic perception in AI-generated content.\n259\tThe fourth subset consists of 4,400 tracks from the Muchin datasetWang et al. [2024], which further\n260\texpands coverage across musical genres and compositional styles.\n261\tThis multi-source construction results in a dataset that spans both human-composed and AI-generated\n262\tmusic, covering a wide range of production qualities, stylistic variations, and emotional characteristics.\n263\tSuch diversity is critical for establishing a robust and generalizable benchmark, enabling evaluation\n264\tacross different creation paradigms and varying aesthetic characteristics.\n265\tWe provide all annotation data and a large subset(7030 songs)of publicly available audios, includes\n266\t2630 songs generated by AI, which can be downloaded on our huggingface page1 , and 4400 songs\n267\tfrom open-source Muchin dataset, which can be downloaded on Muchin’s github page2 . Other\n268\tcopyrighted audios are not allowed to be released due to licensing constraints.\n269\t3.4\n270\t\n271\tAnnotators\n272\t\n273\tThe dataset is annotated by 30 annotators, each treated as an independent rating source in our analysis.\n274\tEach music track is independently evaluated by an average of 10 annotators, enabling robust estimation of inter-rater agreement and stable aggregation of aesthetic scores. This multi-annotator design\n275\thelps reduce individual bias and supports reliable statistical analysis of perceptual consistency.\n276\tTo ensure annotation quality, we adopt a three-stage quality control pipeline. The first stage consists\n277\tof the primary annotation process. In the second stage, 20% of the annotations are randomly sampled\n278\tfor review and consistency checking. In the third stage, an additional 10% of the annotations are\n279\trandomly selected for further validation by a different reviewer. The review and validation stages are\n280\tconducted independently to reduce confirmation bias and improve reliability.\n281\tAnnotators were recruited from multiple music conservatories, media universities, and industry\n282\tpartners across several institutions. All annotators had received at least three years of formal\n283\tprofessional music training, and all held a bachelor’s degree or higher. This ensured that raters\n284\tpossessed sufficient musical knowledge and listening expertise to provide consistent and informed\n285\tevaluations. Quality control and secondary review were conducted by senior experts with formal\n286\tmusic training and professional evaluation experience, each with more than ten years of professional\n287\tmusic education background.\n288\t3.5\n289\t\n290\tAnnotation Statistics and Distribution\n291\t\n292\tWe analyze the distribution of aesthetic scores across all dimensions. As shown in Fig. 2, scores are\n293\tpredominantly concentrated in the mid-to-high range (approximately 2.5–4.5), with relatively few\n294\textreme values. This reflects a common characteristic of human aesthetic evaluation, where most\n295\tmusic is perceived as moderately good rather than strongly polarized. Such a distribution implies a\n296\tlimited dynamic range, making fine-grained regression particularly challenging.\n297\t1 https://huggingface.co/datasets/sirui1/MADB-Dataset\n298\t2 https://github.com/CarlWangChina/MuChin\n299\t\n300\t5\n301\t\n302\t\fFigure 2: Histograms of average score across dimensions\n303\t\n304\tWe further evaluate annotation consistency using the Intraclass Correlation Coefficient (ICCK) The\n305\tresults are all around 0.8, indicate strong multi-rater reliability across most dimensions, supporting\n306\tthe stability and validity of the aggregated scores.\n307\t\n308\t4\n309\t\n310\tExperiments\n311\t\n312\tFigure 3: Three categories of evaluated methods: (1) pretrained encoders with post-training, (2)\n313\tCLAP with semantic adaptation, and (3) LLM-based evaluation.\n314\t\n315\t4.1\n316\t\n317\tPretraining and Evaluation Framework\n318\t\n319\tWe build upon the CLAP framework Wu et al. [2024] by incorporating semantic supervision from\n320\tboth textual comments and structured tags (e.g., genre and mood).\n321\tAll comments are originally written in Chinese and translated into English using Qwen2.5Instruct Qwen et al. [2025] for CLAP’s training, both original Chinese comments and translated\n322\tEnglish comments are provided. For each audio sample, multiple annotator comments are encoded\n323\tand aggregated via mean pooling to form a unified textual representation. In parallel, genre and\n324\tmood tags are embedded into low-dimensional vectors and projected into the same embedding space.\n325\tThe two representations are fused through a learnable gating mechanism to produce a joint semantic\n326\tembedding.\n327\t6\n328\t\n329\t\fTo enhance audio–semantic alignment, we perform a pre-adaptation stage based on contrastive\n330\tlearning. Specifically, the audio encoder is trained to align with the fused semantic representation\n331\tusing a cosine similarity-based objective. This stage relies only on comments and tags, without using\n332\taesthetic scores, thereby avoiding label leakage while encouraging the model to capture perceptual\n333\tand semantic information.\n334\tFor downstream evaluation, we adopt a unified regression framework across all models. Audio representations extracted from pretrained encoders are temporally pooled into fixed-length embeddings,\n335\tfollowed by a Transformer-based regression head to predict aesthetic scores. Models are trained using\n336\tmean squared error (MSE) as the primary objective, optionally combined with a correlation-based\n337\tloss to better align predictions with human perceptual rankings.\n338\tWe evaluate multiple encoder variants, including MuQ, MERT, and CLAP, as well as CLAP adapted\n339\twith comment-only and comment–tag supervision. All models share the same downstream architecture, differing only in encoder and pretraining strategy, enabling a controlled comparison of\n340\trepresentation quality. The encoders are frozen during downstream training.\n341\tWe randomly split the dataset into training and validation sets with a fixed ratio. All models are\n342\toptimized using Adam with a consistent set of hyperparameters across experiments. During training,\n343\tzero values indicate non-applicable dimensions and are excluded from optimization, with separate\n344\tmodels trained when necessary. All clap-based experiments are conducted with 4 fixed random\n345\tseeds(42,120,5,2500) to ensure reproducibility and to reduce the influence of stochastic factors such\n346\tas data shuffling, parameter initialization, and mini-batch sampling. Muq and Mert experiments are\n347\tunder seed 42.\n348\tAll experiments are conducted on NVIDIA A100 GPUs for embedding extraction and pretraining,\n349\tand NVIDIA Tesla V100 GPUs for downstream training.\n350\tTable 2: Performance comparison across different metrics and aesthetic dimensions.(mean+std)\n351\tMetric Method\n352\t\n353\tMSE↓\n354\t\n355\tLCC↑\n356\t\n357\tMel. Emo.\n358\t\n359\tArr. Perc.\n360\t\n361\tArr. Emo.\n362\t\n363\tRhy. Perc.\n364\t\n365\tMERT\n366\t\n367\t1\n368\t\n369\t0.090\n370\t\n371\t0.083\n372\t\n373\t0.111\n374\t\n375\t0.108\n376\t\n377\t0.079\n378\t\n379\t0.098\n380\t\n381\t0.079\n382\t\n383\t0.096\n384\t\n385\t0.091\n386\t\n387\t0.135\n388\t\n389\tMuQ\n390\t\n391\t0.081\n392\t\n393\t0.070\n394\t\n395\t0.075\n396\t\n397\t0.064\n398\t\n399\t0.062\n400\t\n401\t0.063\n402\t\n403\t0.081\n404\t\n405\t0.076\n406\t\n407\t0.075\n408\t\n409\t0.074\n410\t\n411\tStruc. Perc. Perf_Sing. Emo. Sing. Skill\n412\t\n413\tPerf. Skill Sound Effect\n414\t\n415\t0.097\n416\t\n417\tCLAP\n418\t\n419\t0.109±0.001 0.110±0.005 0.121±0.009 0.125±0.006 0.123±0.010 0.103±0.005 0.101±0.008\n420\t\n421\t0.135±0.004\n422\t\n423\t0.145±0.006 0.121±0.004 0.158±0.007\n424\t\n425\tCLAP+C\n426\t\n427\t0.108±0.007 0.111±0.005 0.118±0.003 0.123±0.008 0.125±0.008 0.105±0.003 0.100±0.004\n428\t\n429\t0.134±0.005\n430\t\n431\t0.139±0.002 0.123±0.002 0.153±0.006\n432\t\n433\tCLAP+C&T 0.109±0.004 0.109±0.006 0.120±0.009 0.120±0.008 0.123±0.003 0.097±0.003 0.098±0.003\n434\t\n435\t0.134±0.008\n436\t\n437\t0.144±0.003 0.121±0.005 0.158±0.005\n438\t\n439\tMERT\n440\t\n441\t0.626\n442\t\n443\t0.670\n444\t\n445\t0.713\n446\t\n447\t0.561\n448\t\n449\t0.567\n450\t\n451\t0.674\n452\t\n453\t0.534\n454\t\n455\t0.782\n456\t\n457\t0.674\n458\t\n459\t0.635\n460\t\n461\t0.600\n462\t\n463\tMuQ\n464\t\n465\t0.718\n466\t\n467\t0.715\n468\t\n469\t0.766\n470\t\n471\t0.680\n472\t\n473\t0.685\n474\t\n475\t0.